<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12137h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12137h">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12137h"> 137(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> new name at death / &amp; for initiation</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In an Appendix I have argued that the <mark>change of name which occurs in connection with ritual death</mark> and rebirth, is also an outcome of the practice of mummification. <font color="green">[On page 201 Perry suggests that the change of name that occurs in rites of <mark>initiation</mark> arose out of an association with the belief that in mummification &lsquo;the person mummified became someone else&rsquo;.]</font> <small> William James Perry, <a name="ORMR" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ORMR"><cite title="source">Origin of Magic and Religion</cite></a> (1923) vii</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c12141e" href="c12all.htm#c12141e">VI.C.12:141(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
